data.output: I wanted the passport to escape. To escape from a country where my liberties would be impeded. I had already spent months trying to fulfil their pre-requisites. The accompanying letter had been sent with the passport application a week earlier, but now in the High Commission office, they were telling me that my application was not complete. Not satisfactory. I would have to re-send it but more than that they required a personalised stamp from the solicitor who had attested to the fact they knew me. How very drole I thought. Perhaps ironic that even the British passport office did not expect me to jump through such hoops. I wondered if the process was worth the effort. Should I stay after all?

Lucy threw the letter on the ground. She was not going to read another word of this rubbish. She stamped on the envelope and screwed her heel into the paper, ripping it. How satisfying, she thought, that'll teach him to send me such dross. She walked out of the room with her head held high, smiling at the feeling of release and closure.

The skill of written communication is dying. Having worked away from home for extended periods of time from loved ones, I would eagerly anticipate the arrival of a letter to pick up my morale. Now we write emails sent electronically, but I used to love a trip to the post box to send my communication instead. Email is easier and prevents the need to purchase a rather expensive stamp to deliver them these days. Electronic emails are instantly sent and received rather than have to specifically take a trip out to send a letter by post.

Jim stepped foot into the car showroom and was browsing the various models and makes of vehicles available in his price range. The manager explained how a diesel car needed long distance driving and was not really suitable for Jim's situation.  Jim finally signed off on a new petrol car, the manager agreed he could drive it off the lot that day if Jim was willing to pump the gas on the way home as it was low in fuel already. Once upon a time there was a retired postman called Edward. Over the years he had become obsessive with collecting stamps. One day he was at a retired postperson convention and he met other stamp collecting enthusiasts. He made a good friend in retired postwoman Sarah, and she showed him a brilliant stamp which seemed to have a moving face (of an ostrich) thanks to the silver holographic effect. They decided to stay in touch by letter to discuss their stamp collections and trade their weird and wonderful stamps. At Christmas Sarah decided to send Edward a letter with a special gift; she had sourced one of the rare ostrich stamps for him. Edward was delighted and decided to frame it.
